    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you decide to turn off the power at the breaker, you should still be cautious. To check if the capacitor might be the issue, you would typically look for signs of bulging or leaking on the capacitor. A healthy capacitor usually has a clear, glass-like outer shell. If you see any discoloration, bulging, or a crack in the shell, it's likely that the capacitor is blown and needs to be replaced.\n\nHowever, even if the capacitor looks fine, other components like the fan motor or the motor's electrical connections might also be causing the issue. A blown fuse, a faulty relay, or a loose connection could also result in the humming sound without the fan blades spinning.\n\nIf you're not experienced with electrical repairs, it's still risky to open the AC unit and inspect it, even with the power off. The internal components can be sensitive, and there's a chance of damaging the system further or causing a short circuit. A professional technician can safely and accurately diagnose the problem, ensuring that any repairs are done correctly and safely.\n\nRemember, while it might be tempting to save money by attempting to fix the issue yourself, it's often more cost-effective in the long run to hire a professional. They can identify the exact problem and provide a proper",
